WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:02.240
Okay.

00:00:02.250 --> 00:00:03.800
Hello, everyone.

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:05.000
I'm Natalie.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:07.360
I'm an investor at Bain Capital Crypto, where

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:10.610
we focus primarily on open protocols and cryptography.

00:00:10.650 --> 00:00:13.710
And we are actually investors in Blue Sky, as well as

00:00:13.750 --> 00:00:16.430
a couple other projects in the ecosystem.

00:00:16.430 --> 00:00:19.600
But I also come here as someone who's just an internet

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:22.880
native and has been publishing original content, music, writing on

00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:24.270
the internet for a while.

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:26.920
And I spend most of my time in my investing capacity,

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:29.400
thinking about new media and new business models.

00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:32.310
And so what I want to talk about here today is,

00:00:32.310 --> 00:00:35.320
you know, I think most people here, we share a

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:37.270
lot of values when it comes to, you know, why

00:00:37.270 --> 00:00:39.840
we're here and what we think is important about this.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:43.350
But I think that for better or worse, I think when

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:46.670
it comes to winning the masses, I do think that we

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:49.950
generally speaking have to sort of win on economics and not just

00:00:50.050 --> 00:00:50.500
values.

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:53.830
And so I think one of the most important and interesting sort

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:56.850
of open questions in this world right now is like, what

00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:59.830
are the sort of economic primitives or substrates or questions

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:02.980
that we should be thinking about when it comes to how we

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:05.420
actually manifest the world that I think a lot of us here

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:07.080
are interested in seeing come to fruition.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:10.730
So maybe just to start off with something very basic.

00:01:10.730 --> 00:01:13.150
You know, when I talk about sovereign media, when we

00:01:13.150 --> 00:01:15.620
talk about sovereign media, what exactly are we talking about?

00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:18.620
And I think for me, it's sort of very basically

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:21.760
, not necessarily a format, but really a paradigm that is

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:25.510
about people having the capacity to own the means of their own

00:01:25.530 --> 00:01:28.370
cultural production, which I think is specifically about, you know

00:01:28.370 --> 00:01:30.560
, do you have control over how your content is produced?

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:34.000
Do you have control over how your content is distributed?

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:35.800
And do you have control over how your content is monetized

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:36.000
?

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.370
And I have this caveat here at the end, about without

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:41.440
sacrificing access to scale, because I think historically, when you

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
look at, you know, go back as far as you

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
want to, I think the kind of Faustian bargain

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
that underlies the media economy has been for a long time

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
that if you're a creator, you know, you will

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
trade some amount of agency, some amount of creative control for

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
access to scale.

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
You know, for me personally, if I had to pick

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
somewhere to fall on here, I think I'd probably want

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:41.440
to fall on the patronage model.

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:42.610
Honestly, I think that comes with a lot of great benefits

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:42.880
.

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:45.870
But, you know, I think generally speaking, this is

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:46.880
kind of the, the bargain that people have in the world

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:46.880
.

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:48.570
And I think that, you know, I think, you

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:50.620
know, I think that there's a lot of great benefits

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:50.880
.

00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:52.680
And I think that's kind of a lot of great benefits

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:52.880
.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:56.980
But, you know, I think generally speaking, this is

00:01:56.980 --> 00:01:57.750
kind of the, the bargain that people have in the world

00:01:57.750 --> 00:01:57.880
.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:01:59.880
And I think that there's a lot of great benefits.

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:01.560
But, you know, I think generally speaking, this is

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:03.120
kind of the, the, the bargain that people have in

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:03.760
the world.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:07.760
And I think that there's a lot of great benefits.

00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:09.880
But, you know, I think generally speaking, this is

00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:10.880
kind of the, the, the bargain that people have in

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:10.880
the world.

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:12.560
The bargain that people find themselves in.

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:14.450
And I don't want to, you know, make this

00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:17.070
sound like it's inherently evil all the time.

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:19.700
I think there are better and worse places to kind of fall

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:20.650
on the spectrum.

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:22.640
But I think it's important to kind of, I think

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:24.540
this is a useful sort of mental model to keep in mind

00:02:24.570 --> 00:02:24.720
.

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:27.720
And obviously, there's some good examples of this.

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:29.510
Like, I think for most people here, like a Google

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:30.910
search where it's like, you know, if you make

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:33.400
yourself illegible to us, you let us index you,

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:35.040
you know, we'll, we'll send you viewers,

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:35.430
right?

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:39.430
So, obviously, there are some trade offs that are associated

00:02:39.430 --> 00:02:40.320
with that.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:42.160
You know, the scale requires standardization.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:43.620
Standardization requires legibility.

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:46.510
And legibility really constrains what gets made.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:48.920
And I think the thing that I kind of wanted to double

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:50.870
click on here is that I think, you know, a

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:53.630
lot of times, again, people here who are in these

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:55.120
spaces share certain values.

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:57.080
And we think privacy is important.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:00.000
But I think it's really important to understand or just to

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
keep in mind that, you know, a lot of times

00:03:03.020 --> 00:03:05.350
the reason why people, you know, will give up their

00:03:05.350 --> 00:03:07.680
privacy or will surveil themselves or allow themselves to be surve

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.310
illed is not just because they don't value those things,

00:03:10.310 --> 00:03:12.720
but because they, there's a real economic cost to that

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:12.920
.

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:14.760
And a lot of times, you know, in our society

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:18.080
, in our intention economy, however you want to call it

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:21.330
, you know, legibility and economic value are very deeply

00:03:21.330 --> 00:03:21.910
intertwined.

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:25.890
And so, oftentimes, when people want to, you know

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:28.480
, if people want to, you know, put privacy first

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:30.760
, that oftentimes associated with a real cost, a real economic

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:31.120
cost.

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:34.120
And so, I think the big point here is like,

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:37.280
thinking about this in terms of a problem that is systemic and

00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:40.120
architectural and not something that is merely the consequence of bad choices

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:40.120
.

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:43.420
So, and I think another thing kind of related to that

00:03:43.490 --> 00:03:48.030
that I think is important to remember is that, you know

00:03:48.090 --> 00:03:50.310
, I think there's a lot of reasons that this is

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:50.320
important.

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:52.320
You know, obviously, we want creators to be paid.

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:55.500
Obviously, we don't want all of our communications infrastructure to

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:56.320
be owned by billionaires.

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:58.430
But I think the bigger point, at least for me,

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:00.720
that I think is important to keep in mind is that,

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.530
you know, there's a kind of incentive flywheel that

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:04.310
's at play here.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:08.160
And I think the real scary thing and the real fundamental problem

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:12.060
that a lot of things like slop or surveillance are really symptoms

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.450
of is this idea that, you know, our incentives kind

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:17.520
of dictate what gets produced.

00:04:17.520 --> 00:04:20.270
What gets produced dictates the quality of our information ecosystem,

00:04:20.270 --> 00:04:22.900
which then dictate our ability to really coordinate and sense make as

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:23.510
a society.

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:26.530
And so, I think the real reason why we want the

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:31.660
economic incentives that underlie our cultural production to be aligned is

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:34.320
because it's really a societal epidemic.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:38.930
problem even more than just a media problem, if you will

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:39.320
.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:41.840
So, with all that context, I want to talk a

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:45.640
little bit about the role of technology, which is the world

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:46.320
that I come from.

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:49.610
And at least in the technology world, we often have this

00:04:49.690 --> 00:04:54.310
sort of belief or assumption that when we, you know,

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:56.800
expand access to things, that that in and of itself is

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:58.700
sort of, you know, the winning recipe, if you

00:04:58.730 --> 00:04:59.320
will.

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:01.960
And, you know, when I was personally spending time on

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:04.670
thinking about this question of, like, you know, why

00:05:04.670 --> 00:05:06.320
do we not live in the sovereign media paradigm?

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:08.970
One thing that I really started to ruminate on,

00:05:08.970 --> 00:05:11.780
well, is, you know, why hasn't democratized

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:16.320
access to the means of cultural production led to a sovereign media

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:16.320
paradigm?

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:17.320
And what do I mean by that?

00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:18.320
And what do I mean by that?

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:20.080
What I mean by that is if you kind of look at

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:23.320
, let's call it, you know, modern attention economy

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:25.510
that I would date going back to roughly the 1830s

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:29.310
with the rise of the penny press, what you see is

00:05:29.310 --> 00:05:32.320
this sort of secular trend of the main inputs coming down.

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:36.190
The cost of production, the cost of distribution has actually been

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:39.320
coming down in a fairly secular way for centuries.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:45.340
And yet the market structure during that time has become as centralized

00:05:45.340 --> 00:05:46.320
as ever.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:48.560
And so I think, you know, that can be a

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:51.080
hard thing to see if we don't sort of zoom out

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:51.320
.

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:54.790
But I think there's a real sort of almost narrative violation

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:57.820
there around how is it that at the same time that access

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:00.580
to what we would call, you know, owning your means

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:02.310
of production has dropped so much.

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:04.610
How is it in that same time that the market structure and

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:07.320
the economic value has become so unbelievably centralized?

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:10.380
And I think a good way to think about this is that

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:13.560
, you know, Facebook and Google simultaneously, you know,

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:16.300
represent the most accessible platforms in a lot of ways.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:19.280
They are they're offering us in some ways free distribution and

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:20.320
free production.

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:23.700
But at the same time, they represent a complete consolidation and

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:26.310
vertical integration of the market structure.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:28.220
And just to kind of give you an example by what I

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:29.970
mean by that, you know, if you go back to

00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:32.200
like the TV era, for example, there was a lot

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:33.320
of consolidation then.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:36.070
But there was a real market structure in the sense that you

00:06:36.070 --> 00:06:39.030
had distributors, you have producers, you had ad exchanges

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:42.650
, you had people who did measurement of audience of audience engagement

00:06:42.650 --> 00:06:43.310
and things like that.

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:45.710
And then if you think about something like Facebook, they are

00:06:45.710 --> 00:06:48.320
completely vertically integrated across all of those things.

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:50.380
They do the measurement, they're the ad exchange, they

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:52.380
're the distributor, they're now with AI, they're

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:53.320
the producer as well.

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:56.200
And so there's this kind of strange bifurcation

00:06:56.200 --> 00:06:58.320
that is, I think, hard to see.

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:01.140
And it's often obscured by the fact that these companies

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:03.910
are offering us free products and services and they're giving us

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:05.320
, you know, so much free distribution.

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:09.320
It's like, how could that possibly be a problem?

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:11.700
And so I think, at least for me, there's

00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:14.710
kind of two lessons that I think I've taken away from

00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:15.310
that.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:19.260
One is this idea that access and economic value seem to operate

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:21.310
really at different levels.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:24.620
Access kind of operates at the layer where the costs are collapsed

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:25.320
, right?

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.150
So when the internet, you know, brings the cost of

00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:29.820
distribution down to zero, now we can all have access to

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:30.320
that.

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:33.320
But economic value consolidates at the new scarcity layer.

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:36.720
So the moment that that happens, actually the most valuable thing

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:40.320
to do is become the aggregator and become the curator.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:42.520
And so there's this weird bifurcation that happens

00:07:42.530 --> 00:07:44.890
there where just at the moment that you get access to the

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:48.730
thing, the economic value has in some way been stripped out

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:49.300
of it.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:52.290
And I think the second kind of related point to that is

00:07:52.290 --> 00:07:55.310
that scale creates new coordination problems.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:58.320
And so, you know, just because access scales, when

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:01.740
access scales but trust does not, that gap is where platform

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:03.310
modes and economics live.

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:05.240
And so, I think in some way, at least for

00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:07.390
me, I think one of the lessons I've taken away

00:08:07.390 --> 00:08:10.610
from this is that trust is really the thing that we have

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:12.910
to scale, I think, in some ways to start to

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:16.090
break out of this sort of Faustian bargain that I

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:18.100
think we've kind of been stuck in for a long time

00:08:18.100 --> 00:08:18.290
.

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:21.420
So, I think, you know, takeaway, technology has

00:08:21.570 --> 00:08:26.010
democratized access in very important and I think very straightforward ways

00:08:26.010 --> 00:08:26.310
.

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:29.110
But it has not democratized economic value in the same ways

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:30.320
or to the same degree.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:31.970
And I think that's kind of a, you know,

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:34.270
at least for people in my industry, generally a bit of

00:08:34.270 --> 00:08:37.320
a hard pill to swallow because we like to think that access

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:41.030
and value are sort of coupled in ways that they may not

00:08:41.040 --> 00:08:41.310
be.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:43.560
So, I want to bring this all to the kind of

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:46.420
current moment and talk about AI, which I'm sure is

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:48.320
everyone's favorite topic.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:50.520
And I think the useful way for me that I like to

00:08:50.540 --> 00:08:53.600
think about AI is that it sort of breaks the existing covenant

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:54.310
, right?

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:56.840
So, in a world of omnipresent AI, we

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:01.300
fall into a situation where your agency can no longer reliably be

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:05.310
traded for access to the economic benefits of scale.

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:07.720
And I think, you know, going back to the Google

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:10.320
example is kind of a perfect one because, you know,

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:12.670
you used to, you know, make your content legible

00:09:12.670 --> 00:09:15.460
to Google, let them index it, and you would have

00:09:15.470 --> 00:09:17.310
faith that they would send you some amount of viewership.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:19.120
Now, with AI, you think of ChatGPT

00:09:19.130 --> 00:09:21.320
as a kind of layer that sits on top of that.

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:25.810
And so you're seeing these crazy numbers about how the impression

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:29.380
to viewership ratios are changing because, you know, A

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:32.310
Is are pinging people's websites thousands and thousands of times

00:09:32.310 --> 00:09:34.320
and sending fewer and fewer viewers.

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:37.000
And so if you are someone who is taking the time to

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
really produce high-quality content, high-quality information,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.800
high-quality cultural production, you find yourself in this weird

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:47.370
space where, in a lot of ways, you're no

00:09:47.470 --> 00:09:50.760
longer economically incentivized to actually put that out on the open

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:51.320
web.

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:55.150
It's actually becoming economically rational for you to pay all that

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:57.310
, for you to put it in private silos.

00:09:57.320 --> 00:09:59.750
And for many cases, people are just actually taking it offline

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:00.320
entirely.

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:02.180
And I mentioned at the end of this presentation that there's

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:04.380
-- I'm noticing, at least in my world, a

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:08.310
rise in physical media publications where people are almost going back to

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:12.760
not just physical books but physical magazines where they actually are skipping

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:16.140
the whole -- they want their distribution to basically be offline in

00:10:16.140 --> 00:10:18.480
many ways so that the AI can't scrape it or train

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:20.320
on it or whatever the case may be.

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:22.590
And I think Cloudflare, who's a sponsor of

00:10:22.590 --> 00:10:25.870
this conference, their CEO has been really loud over the last

00:10:25.870 --> 00:10:29.500
year about this dynamic and has actually been trying to offer some

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:32.520
services to creators that allow them to pay all their content to

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:33.320
AI agents.

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:35.920
But I think, you know, there are also challenges with

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:39.310
that -- with that setup for many reasons.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:42.730
So I think the challenge with this is that it's creating

00:10:42.730 --> 00:10:45.310
this kind of a legible web, if you will,

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:49.440
which is what I was just speaking about, where people are

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:52.120
incentivized if you are -- the more kind of care and

00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:54.110
quality that you're putting into your work in a certain way

00:10:54.110 --> 00:10:57.550
, the more incentivized you are to sort of, you

00:10:57.550 --> 00:11:00.170
know, keep it closed off, keep it paywalled

00:11:00.170 --> 00:11:02.310
, keep it, you know, siloed.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:04.590
And so it's -- I think the outcome of that,

00:11:04.590 --> 00:11:06.690
if you play that out long enough, is that all the

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:09.320
good stuff is basically hidden, paywalled and available.

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:12.380
And the open free web is largely just kind of, you

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:15.820
know, various forms and flavors of AI slot, which I

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:19.410
think to some degree we are already feeling that and living in

00:11:19.420 --> 00:11:20.310
that a little bit.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:23.400
So, you know, these are some kind of somewhat funny

00:11:23.570 --> 00:11:26.920
tweets that I saw that I think kind of capture this sentiment

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:29.300
in the zeitgeist in different ways.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:32.070
But I think, you know, this is kind of where

00:11:32.070 --> 00:11:35.310
we are, quite frankly, in the current moment.

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:38.320
So, you know, the opportunity for app protocol.

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:40.320
Where does app protocol fit into something like this?

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:42.920
And I think, for me, having -- you know,

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:47.320
using this framing, I think the most interesting and important thing

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:49.320
about open web protocols and cryptography, in a lot of

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:53.930
ways, is that they ease this tension between scale and agency

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:54.320
.

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:56.060
Where you don't, in the same way, have to

00:11:56.060 --> 00:12:02.320
-- getting access to scale does not require the same sacrificing of

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:05.320
agency in the same ways.

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:07.120
And so, you know, this is kind of a sort

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:09.320
of a funny thing, but I do mean it seriously,

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:12.450
where I think that part of what we're seeing here is

00:12:12.450 --> 00:12:15.310
a -- part of what we're seeing here is a return

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:18.320
to gatekeeping in a certain sense.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:24.230
That's where people are -- people are wanting to not be

00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:27.300
forced into one sort of mode or the other.

00:12:27.320 --> 00:12:30.040
And they want to be able to play around the design space

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:32.780
that allows you to have some amount of scale and some amount

00:12:32.850 --> 00:12:33.310
of agency.

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:35.220
And I think, you know, there are some examples I

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:37.320
talk about towards the end of this presentation.

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:39.180
But I think even just as a basic one that people here

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:41.090
are familiar with, you know, I used to think about

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:43.970
something like a black sky, where, you know, you

00:12:43.970 --> 00:12:47.030
have a place for your community that is, you know,

00:12:47.030 --> 00:12:48.320
for you and is specialized.

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:51.310
But that doesn't in any way preclude you from being

00:12:51.310 --> 00:12:54.820
, you know, very deeply tapped into and integrated with a

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:57.320
wider, more scaled web and more scaled experience.

00:12:57.320 --> 00:12:59.430
And so I think, you know, open enough to scale

00:12:59.470 --> 00:13:02.060
, close enough to actually mean something is a good way to

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:03.940
think about, you know, where I think a lot of

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:05.310
people increasingly want to fall here.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:07.770
And I think some of this is not even just an economics

00:13:07.770 --> 00:13:08.320
thing.

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:10.560
I think increasingly I was joking with a friend the other day

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:13.420
that being famous is not really fun anymore because it intrinsically

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:16.890
comes with so much, you know, to be exposed like

00:13:16.890 --> 00:13:20.660
that in the open web, you expose yourself to so much

00:13:20.680 --> 00:13:23.320
harassment and so much negativity that I think people are finding --

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:26.230
it's getting to a point where some people wonder, like

00:13:26.230 --> 00:13:28.320
, is it worth me even being online?

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:29.950
Is it worth me even, you know, trying to maintain

00:13:29.950 --> 00:13:31.320
this public presence in the same way?

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:33.560
It feels like it really takes a toll on people in a

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:34.320
lot of ways.

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:37.070
And so, you know, I think in a lot of

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:41.320
ways, at least in my personal opinion, the successful outcomes

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:44.460
and what types of things will be interesting to build here will

00:13:44.470 --> 00:13:46.890
look a lot more like guilds and collectives than traditional

00:13:46.890 --> 00:13:47.320
startups.

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:50.540
And so I love the previous speaker who was just here because

00:13:50.540 --> 00:13:53.000
, you know, what he was speaking about in a lot

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.070
of ways is exactly this, just kind of for the journalism

00:13:56.070 --> 00:13:58.820
era where you have all these different sorts of new ways of

00:13:58.820 --> 00:14:03.320
, you know, coordinating with people and forming new types of

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:07.370
-- basically new types of institutions in a lot of ways to

00:14:07.370 --> 00:14:09.310
serve your community.

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:11.040
And, yeah, I think thinking about it in terms of

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:13.320
new institutions is really a useful way to think about it.

00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:15.700
But I think, you know, it's funny for me

00:14:15.700 --> 00:14:18.320
as a VC because I think a lot of this stuff will

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:21.360
and even goes for us to say should be eligible to venture

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:22.320
capital in a lot of ways.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:30.060
I think these sorts of entities will be -- the economic subst

00:14:30.060 --> 00:14:32.310
rates that they will have to exist in will be different.

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:34.610
And I think the funding structures, it goes all the way

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:35.320
down to that.

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:38.920
And so I think just to kind of post to the audience

00:14:38.930 --> 00:14:41.570
, I think a good -- a useful question to ask is

00:14:41.570 --> 00:14:44.850
kind of like, where are people already experimenting with high-

00:14:44.860 --> 00:14:46.320
quality culture production?

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:49.320
And where's infrastructure for that missing?

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:50.810
And at least for me, I think I have a couple

00:14:50.810 --> 00:14:52.990
examples that I'll share with you guys that I think are

00:14:52.990 --> 00:14:55.310
interesting experiments that are also being run.

00:14:55.320 --> 00:14:57.840
Obviously, I think there's been a lot of talk here

00:14:57.870 --> 00:15:01.310
at AppRoto already about the research and science communities.

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:03.830
And I think that's a great and really, really,

00:15:03.830 --> 00:15:06.320
really interesting space to spend time in.

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:09.340
And I don't know how many people here are familiar specifically

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:12.030
with the biohacking peptide community, but there are

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:14.810
communities of people who are now sort of doing scientific experiments on

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:15.320
themselves.

00:15:15.320 --> 00:15:19.400
They're sharing health protocols, and it's this weird sort

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:23.320
of thing where it's almost like this new kind of scientific

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:25.310
or research institution.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:30.090
And you can imagine that there's a certain level of infrastructure

00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:33.070
that will be needed for that, whether it's verifying

00:15:33.070 --> 00:15:35.600
that or testing to certain protocols that you've taken or that

00:15:35.600 --> 00:15:36.320
you haven't taken.

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:38.810
Or people being able to trust, obviously, in a context

00:15:38.810 --> 00:15:41.710
where you're essentially giving people medical advice in a lot of

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:42.310
cases.

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:45.860
But you can imagine that that will need more infrastructure, especially

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:49.030
in the case of verification, than just your run of the

00:15:49.030 --> 00:15:51.300
mill social media platform.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:53.520
I think a lot of the work that's being done by

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:57.030
the Blue Sky team with permission data is incredible because that's

00:15:57.110 --> 00:16:00.550
exactly the kind of architectural primitives that we will need to

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:02.320
open up this design space a lot more.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:05.320
And I'm incredibly, incredibly excited about that.

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:07.320
There's also this idea of community computing.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.120
I don't know how many people here are familiar with the

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:10.320
dark forest operating system.

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:13.100
I honestly wish this project was built on top of that protocol

00:16:13.100 --> 00:16:13.320
.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:15.320
I'm kind of sold to that it's not.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:17.320
But this is essentially like community operating spaces.

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:20.620
And so you can sort of create a, a lot of

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:22.780
them have, they have, you know, sort of like

00:16:22.790 --> 00:16:24.320
mini wallets and banks inside.

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:25.320
They have sort of community apps.

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:27.290
And you can really think about it as a kind of like

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:28.320
community computer.

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:30.830
And these are sort of meant to be, again, like

00:16:30.830 --> 00:16:33.450
they're not closed off in the sense of like, you

00:16:33.450 --> 00:16:35.830
know, they're super, super private, but they are

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:36.310
closed.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:40.620
They are secluded from the wider web in sort of important

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:41.320
ways.

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:43.150
And then obviously, you know, cultural collectives like Black

00:16:43.150 --> 00:16:47.630
Sky and many of the other groups like that, that people

00:16:47.630 --> 00:16:48.320
will be familiar with.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:52.250
And so kind of close out here, I think just maybe

00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:54.940
the short way of putting this whole talk is that, you

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:57.300
know, the economic medium is the message.

00:16:57.320 --> 00:16:59.430
And so I think, I think, you know, as

00:16:59.460 --> 00:17:02.140
we kind of continue to grapple with, you know,

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:05.100
what, what, what, what is this new paradigm going

00:17:05.100 --> 00:17:06.300
to look like?

00:17:06.320 --> 00:17:08.840
I think it's important for us to kind of keep in

00:17:08.870 --> 00:17:12.400
mind that as the primitives and the architecture changes, the

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:13.320
economics will have to change as much.

00:17:13.320 --> 00:17:16.390
And so, you know, even though there's always going

00:17:16.390 --> 00:17:18.710
to be a bit of a, a tendency to think back

00:17:18.750 --> 00:17:20.890
on, you know, how can we do ads or how

00:17:20.890 --> 00:17:23.220
can we do, you know, these things or that things

00:17:23.220 --> 00:17:25.660
, you know, we will have to kind of a little

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:29.320
bit suspend our imagination here and understand that the, the,

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:31.990
the economic primitives that make sense are going to be really

00:17:32.010 --> 00:17:33.320
native to the form factors in a lot of ways.

00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:35.180
And I think that's, you know, that's,

00:17:35.180 --> 00:17:37.590
that's probably the, the main point that I wanted to

00:17:37.590 --> 00:17:38.320
make here.

00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:39.320
So thank you guys so much.

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:40.320
That's all I have for you.

00:17:40.320 --> 00:17:42.720
And I'm happy to take any questions if, if anyone

00:17:42.730 --> 00:17:43.320
has any.

00:17:43.330 --> 00:17:50.320
Excellent.

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:51.320
Thank you very much.

00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:52.320
There's a lot of chat happening on the stream.

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:54.950
So I just want to acknowledge everybody that's tuning in right

00:17:54.950 --> 00:17:55.320
now.

00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:58.320
So we have a few minutes for questions here.

00:17:58.320 --> 00:18:02.320
Anybody have anything they want to ask Natalie?

00:18:02.320 --> 00:18:07.320
Oh, oh, oh, oh, great.

00:18:07.320 --> 00:18:08.320
Here we go.

00:18:08.320 --> 00:18:11.320
Thank you for the talk.

00:18:11.320 --> 00:18:13.320
Love those ideas you're presenting.

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:18.900
So one, I was interested in how you thought about the

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:21.950
role of curation, because I feel like that sort of

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:26.320
overlaps the scale, agency, economics, gatekeeping,

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:27.320
a word you use.

00:18:27.320 --> 00:18:30.060
Like, do you see gatekeeping as similar to curation

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:30.320
?

00:18:30.320 --> 00:18:31.320
Is there overlap there?

00:18:31.320 --> 00:18:32.320
I think so.

00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:34.190
I think it's more like a localized curation is the

00:18:34.190 --> 00:18:36.470
way I would think about it, where, you know,

00:18:36.490 --> 00:18:38.440
a lot of these platforms right now are kind of built on

00:18:38.480 --> 00:18:41.000
a, a more global curation where it's, you

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.440
know, it's the, it's the, it's

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:44.070
the algorithm that's amassing, you know, all this

00:18:44.070 --> 00:18:44.320
, all these sorts of things.

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:46.560
And it's, and it's, and it's not

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:50.130
the way in which content is being curated is, I guess

00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:53.110
it's personalized, but it isn't, it isn't

00:18:53.110 --> 00:18:57.320
attuned to the local context of a particular community.

00:18:57.320 --> 00:18:58.520
And it's not the way that's curated by people that

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:00.340
's curated by people that's curated by people who are knowledgeable

00:19:00.340 --> 00:19:01.320
about that particular topic.

00:19:01.320 --> 00:19:03.320
It's just kind of this flattened global experience.

00:19:03.320 --> 00:19:05.490
And so I think part of what I'm trying to get

00:19:05.490 --> 00:19:08.600
at there is that, especially with the gatekeeping and like

00:19:08.620 --> 00:19:11.730
the guilds is that that role, which is itself economically

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:14.880
valuable, should in some ways be returned to the context in

00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:16.320
which they are economically valuable.

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:19.610
And in which people have, you know, real understanding and

00:19:19.690 --> 00:19:22.010
of what that should be and can, you know, be

00:19:22.010 --> 00:19:25.810
in conversation and governance and all those sorts of things about how

00:19:25.810 --> 00:19:28.320
to actually do that in a way that makes sense.

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:31.840
Just to tap, tap in on that, in your,

00:19:31.840 --> 00:19:34.950
you know, you're looking at a lot of different startups

00:19:34.950 --> 00:19:37.300
and all, you know, across the space.

00:19:37.320 --> 00:19:39.630
What are you seeing in terms of how AI is like a

00:19:39.630 --> 00:19:42.470
new metal layer for curation, you know, between all

00:19:42.470 --> 00:19:45.360
the content and then the humans that are, that have the

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:48.860
tastes, that have the capability to curate for their communities

00:19:48.940 --> 00:19:49.310
?

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:52.830
Yeah, I think truthfully, I've been a little

00:19:52.830 --> 00:19:57.310
bit, I've been a little bit disappointed or I feel

00:19:57.310 --> 00:19:58.910
like I haven't seen, I haven't seen, I

00:19:58.910 --> 00:20:02.930
think, I think that space is promising because AI is interesting

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:06.150
and that you can wield that scale in terms of personal agency

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:06.320
.

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:08.770
But I guess it's kind of the way you're framing

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:11.290
it, but I haven't seen anything yet that I feel

00:20:11.290 --> 00:20:13.320
like really hits the nail there.

00:20:13.320 --> 00:20:16.070
I think part of what I'm sort of gesturing towards

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:18.470
with this talk is that curation is in a lot of

00:20:18.470 --> 00:20:21.310
ways a very human and context dependent job.

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:23.620
It is, it is very, it's economically valuable in

00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:24.320
that sense.

00:20:24.320 --> 00:20:26.630
And that I think, you know, part of what,

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:29.950
part of what will restore our sense of community and like ability

00:20:29.950 --> 00:20:34.310
to engage in meaning making online is that that function gets returned

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:35.310
to human beings to some degree.

00:20:35.320 --> 00:20:37.050
I think, you know, obviously we can't sift

00:20:37.050 --> 00:20:39.320
through all the millions and millions of content.

00:20:39.320 --> 00:20:42.280
But I do think that, I do think that before we

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:45.540
can talk more about kind of how the role that AI plays

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:48.300
in that, I do think there's the more pressing conversation

00:20:48.310 --> 00:20:52.210
is restoring that functionality to humans a little bit is the way

00:20:52.210 --> 00:20:53.320
I would think about it.

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:54.320
Thank you.

00:20:54.320 --> 00:20:56.320
Right in the back here.

00:20:56.320 --> 00:20:57.320
Yeah.

00:20:57.320 --> 00:21:00.390
So on the topic of guilds and collectives as like

00:21:00.510 --> 00:21:04.460
kind of the new formation, how do you think about those

00:21:04.460 --> 00:21:11.320
kinds of structures getting the right capital formation together?

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:15.290
Because one of the things that I've observed on my startup

00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:19.000
journey is that a lot of times VCs are pattern matching

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:24.150
and looking for more traditional two founders owning the vast majority of

00:21:24.160 --> 00:21:27.570
the company, when a guild and collective has like all this

00:21:27.570 --> 00:21:29.320
, you know, kind of governance complexity.

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:30.320
Yeah, great question.

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:33.040
I mean, the first part of that question is, I

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:35.400
think that's, that's a good, that's a

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:37.890
good example of why I think VC is a hard and not

00:21:37.890 --> 00:21:40.310
ideal funding route for a lot of this stuff.

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:44.050
Because venture, venture masters simply requires scale at a certain point

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:44.320
.

00:21:44.320 --> 00:21:46.430
And so if you are not angling for that, it

00:21:46.450 --> 00:21:49.800
will distort your incentives in exactly the kind of the ways that

00:21:49.850 --> 00:21:53.300
I was getting towards at the beginning of the presentation.

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:54.320
So maybe that's one point.

00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:57.120
I think maybe a secondary point is, I think we're

00:21:57.120 --> 00:21:59.800
, we're kind of back to maybe the person who was

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:02.320
presenting before me, we're kind of in the midst of

00:22:02.320 --> 00:22:06.180
that experiment now where people are, you know, trying to

00:22:06.180 --> 00:22:08.650
, you know, make new formations and explore, you know

00:22:08.650 --> 00:22:11.700
, philanthropy or, you know, having a more direct relationship

00:22:11.700 --> 00:22:15.310
with those who, those who consume your content.

00:22:15.320 --> 00:22:17.170
But I do, I do think that remains a little bit

00:22:17.170 --> 00:22:18.980
, I think, I think that remains a little bit of

00:22:18.980 --> 00:22:20.970
an open question in the sense that I don't have like

00:22:20.970 --> 00:22:22.320
a specific primitive to give you.

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:25.920
But I do think that for most things, the, the

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:29.000
, what ends up, what ends up being the kind of

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:33.160
economic mechanism that sustains you will be very native and specific

00:22:33.160 --> 00:22:35.320
to how you actually generate value in your community.

00:22:35.320 --> 00:22:36.320
Right.

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:39.340
So like journalism is monetized and it's valued differently than

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:40.320
like visual media, for example.

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:43.420
And so I wouldn't expect a guild that is built around

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:47.890
the production of journalism or to have the same business model or

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:50.730
funding structure as a guild that's built around, you know

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:53.320
, the production of, you know, paintings, for example

00:22:53.320 --> 00:22:53.320
.

00:22:53.320 --> 00:22:55.400
I don't know, just to take something else, I

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:57.610
think, and maybe that's part of my point is that

00:22:57.610 --> 00:22:59.970
, you know, I think the business models have to be

00:22:59.970 --> 00:23:05.650
more, more local and more form specific, I think is

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:09.320
part of what's happening here.

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:14.320
What are your thoughts on micropayments?

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:18.420
Do you see any viable future for that as a means of

00:23:18.450 --> 00:23:21.310
supporting creative output?

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:22.830
I'm, I, the verdict is still out for me

00:23:22.830 --> 00:23:23.320
on that.

00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:26.320
You know, for example, like Cloudflare is,

00:23:26.320 --> 00:23:28.570
Cloudflare's model, as I understand it, involves

00:23:28.570 --> 00:23:30.780
some sort of micropayments where the idea is that

00:23:30.780 --> 00:23:33.790
you will paywall your content to AI agents and they will

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:34.320
do a micropayment.

00:23:34.320 --> 00:23:37.120
Quite frankly, in the crypto space, there's a lot

00:23:37.120 --> 00:23:39.770
of hype around that right now, and I'm not closed

00:23:39.770 --> 00:23:41.770
off to it, but I guess I just, I haven

00:23:41.770 --> 00:23:43.300
't seen it play out yet.

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:45.610
And I'm also sensitive to the fact that, you know

00:23:45.650 --> 00:23:47.320
, creators have bottom lines.

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:49.040
And so, you know, I think for a lot of

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:51.620
people, at least in my personal experience, a lot of

00:23:51.620 --> 00:23:54.200
people, even though it's not perfect, would prefer a

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:57.030
kind of a sub stack model to a micropayment

00:23:57.030 --> 00:23:57.310
.

00:23:57.320 --> 00:24:01.020
You know, I think recurring revenue is something that creators are

00:24:01.020 --> 00:24:02.320
very interested in.

00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:03.550
And so, you know, I'm, I'm not

00:24:03.550 --> 00:24:05.860
closed off to it, but I haven't seen a formulation

00:24:05.860 --> 00:24:09.310
of it yet that feels like it's really deeply sustainable,

00:24:09.320 --> 00:24:09.320
I guess.

00:24:09.320 --> 00:24:12.320
Yeah, just to follow up on that.

00:24:12.320 --> 00:24:14.780
So in London at Protocols for Publishers just last

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:16.960
month, micropayments was a topic that came up

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:19.650
as it comes up every time we gather together people, you

00:24:19.650 --> 00:24:22.590
know, and there's a lot of research that has gone

00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:24.910
back and looked at micropayments over the last 15

00:24:24.930 --> 00:24:25.320
, 20 years.

00:24:25.320 --> 00:24:29.600
Night Media Forum also hosted a bunch of people talking about that

00:24:29.600 --> 00:24:31.310
just recently as well.

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:32.960
But there's like two things I want to raise at that

00:24:32.960 --> 00:24:33.320
point.

00:24:33.320 --> 00:24:38.830
One is speed, the very simple way to be able to

00:24:38.830 --> 00:24:40.300
like tap to pay.

00:24:40.320 --> 00:24:43.580
Like one of the challenges that we have right now on the

00:24:43.690 --> 00:24:47.050
open web is that it is not easy without installing an extra

00:24:47.050 --> 00:24:49.420
, you know, a plugin or something like a wallet and

00:24:49.450 --> 00:24:50.310
all of this type of stuff.

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:52.320
And so that's, that's a challenge.

00:24:52.320 --> 00:24:54.840
It has to be much smoother, just like going on the

00:24:54.880 --> 00:24:57.070
subway and just like tapping to go through like tap to pay

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:59.300
, we have to get to that smooth UX.

00:24:59.320 --> 00:25:06.770
Another thing is, is in the media world, a lot

00:25:06.810 --> 00:25:09.620
of, it isn't just a matter of how much a

00:25:09.620 --> 00:25:10.310
person paid.

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:12.910
So like when an article comes up and a paywall comes

00:25:12.910 --> 00:25:15.880
up and that article has like a certain value attached to it

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:18.310
for advertising revenue.

00:25:18.320 --> 00:25:19.820
And the idea is like, Oh, great.

00:25:19.820 --> 00:25:22.320
If you just like for people that are not subscribing and they

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:24.760
just micropayment, you just collect enough microp

00:25:24.790 --> 00:25:27.420
ayments, very tiny little micropayments to be

00:25:27.450 --> 00:25:29.310
able to get that advertising equivalent to that advertising value.

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:29.930
You're fine.

00:25:29.930 --> 00:25:30.320
Right.

00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:32.730
But that's not actually how the economics of a lot of

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:34.320
these large newspapers work.

00:25:34.320 --> 00:25:38.910
They package their audiences and sell that information and data and like

00:25:38.980 --> 00:25:40.310
open that up on a different market.

00:25:40.320 --> 00:25:42.350
There's a lot going on behind the scenes that that is

00:25:42.350 --> 00:25:43.320
not accounting for.

00:25:43.320 --> 00:25:44.310
And that's also a challenge.

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:47.580
So even if you'd have to really, it's not

00:25:47.600 --> 00:25:49.110
just a sense of like, can we hit the, like

00:25:49.110 --> 00:25:51.310
the 30 cents, you know, it's actually a lot

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:52.310
more than that.

00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:53.320
So that's another challenge.

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:55.320
Yeah.

00:25:55.570 --> 00:25:57.320
Hi.

00:25:57.320 --> 00:26:00.310
Uh, there was mention of bifurcations,

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:07.290
uh, in reference to what I was, uh, considering

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:09.950
more, maybe, uh, I was thinking more of the

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.950
term partition, but like with bifurcation, I

00:26:13.950 --> 00:26:19.060
imagine like a splitting into, uh, two modes of behavior

00:26:19.070 --> 00:26:19.320
.

00:26:19.320 --> 00:26:24.410
Uh, also with regard to the partition, uh, I

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:29.310
guess I also noticed it in the political sphere, uh,

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:33.840
as most evident in like Epstein's email with, uh

00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:37.590
, Peter Thiel, where he said Brexit was just the

00:26:37.590 --> 00:26:42.120
beginning and that like, there was like, uh, uh

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:46.320
, return to tribalism and a shift away from globalization,

00:26:46.320 --> 00:26:51.580
which I guess spans more than just the media ecosystem, the

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:54.310
political and cultural aspects as well.

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:58.320
But I was thinking of partitions cause like people are,

00:26:58.320 --> 00:27:03.020
uh, yeah, separating from each other, I guess.

00:27:03.020 --> 00:27:06.440
So was there, uh, by, uh, multiple modes

00:27:06.440 --> 00:27:09.290
of behavior that you were referencing with bifurcation?

00:27:09.320 --> 00:27:10.320
Yeah.

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:11.490
So the, what I, what I really meant by the

00:27:11.510 --> 00:27:13.820
bifurcation was that I, I think that the

00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:16.390
, the, the, the, it's kind of like

00:27:16.390 --> 00:27:18.650
the, the, the dynamics of the open web sort of

00:27:18.650 --> 00:27:21.600
increasingly being incentivized to kind of be, you know,

00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:25.090
the freely accessible, like lower quality, lower brow kind of

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:26.320
more sloppish stuff.

00:27:26.320 --> 00:27:28.430
And then the, the, the part on the other side

00:27:28.470 --> 00:27:30.560
of the partition, if you will, is, you know

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:33.650
, all of the more higher quality, more private, more

00:27:33.650 --> 00:27:36.310
, more, you know, intimate, if you will,

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:39.780
more, uh, more local stuff where people feel at least

00:27:39.780 --> 00:27:41.320
right now that, that people are scared.

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:42.320
People are scared.

00:27:42.320 --> 00:27:43.860
I think to put their, to, to put the stuff

00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:45.840
that they really deeply labor over, you know, in the

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:48.320
open web sometimes because you're willing to get trained on,

00:27:48.320 --> 00:27:50.210
you know, where we don't, we don't know

00:27:50.210 --> 00:27:52.310
, uh, sort of, it's more nebulous

00:27:52.310 --> 00:27:54.320
how you can capture the economic value.

00:27:54.320 --> 00:27:56.990
Once you've done that, especially in the world where everyone

00:27:56.990 --> 00:27:59.320
's clawed by is crawling the internet at all times.

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:01.320
And so that's kind of what I was speaking of.

00:28:01.320 --> 00:28:04.310
And, and, you know, this kind of like that

00:28:04.310 --> 00:28:06.500
sort of a bifurcation between the illegible web

00:28:06.500 --> 00:28:08.180
, as I call it, and the more legible web

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:08.320
.

00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:09.320
Excellent.

00:28:09.320 --> 00:28:09.880
All right.

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:12.020
Well, I think we should close off there and give us

00:28:12.020 --> 00:28:14.310
a minute or two to transition to the next session.

00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:16.310
But thank you very much, Natalie, for your analysis.
